Coal, ONGC, Reliance, State Bank, Tata: India Stocks Preview

-- B y   A n d r e w   M a c A s k i l l   a n d   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 
2011-07-07T03:12:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-07/reliance-industries-ongc-tata-steel-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the last close, unless
otherwise stated.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell
0.1 percent to 18,726.97. The BSE 200 Index slid 0.1 percent to
2,319.28. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock Exchange
declined 0.1 percent to 5,625.45. SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index
futures for July delivery gained 0.1 percent to 5,644 as of
10:51 a.m. in  Singapore .  Coal India Ltd. (COAL)  : India may sell an additional
stake in the world’s largest producer of the fuel to employees
who passed up the nation’s biggest initial public offering
because of union pressure, Coal Minister Sriprakash Jaiswal
said. The shares fell 0.8 percent to 392.15 rupees.  Dr. Reddy’s Laboratories Ltd. (DRRD IN): The U.S.  Food and
Drug Administration  has imposed an import ban on products made
at Dr. Reddy’s Mexico plant, the  Press Trust of India  reported,
citing a notice from the regulator. The stock fell 2.3 percent
to 1,528.9 rupees.  Oil & Natural Gas Corp. (ONGC IN): India’s biggest energy
explorer continues to disagree with AFK Sistema on the price it
will pay for a 25 percent stake in OAO Bashneft, a regional
Russian oil producer, said Sistema Chairman Vladimir
Yevtushenkov. The shares fell 1.4 percent to 272.75 rupees.  Reliance Industries Ltd. (RIL)  : Reliance’s plan to sell
stakes in 23 oil and gas blocks it operates to BP Plc for $7.2
billion may get cabinet approval next week, an oil ministry
official with knowledge of the matter said.  Separately, the company exported 30 percent less fuel last
month as jet-fuel shipments fell from this year’s peak in May,
according to transmissions and vessel chartering tracked by
Bloomberg and data from Clarkson Research Services Ltd. Shares
of the owner of the world’s largest refining complex rose 0.8
percent to 852.9 rupees.  State Bank of India (SBIN)  : The biggest lender plans to
open a unit in  Ghana , the Business and Financial Times newspaper
reported, citing Naresh Kumar Malhotra, deputy general manager
of the bank. The lender wants to increase the contribution of
overseas operations to group profit to 25 percent in five years
from 16 percent, the Accra-based newspaper reported. The shares
dropped 1.2 percent to 2,443.85 rupees.  Tata Steel Ltd. (TATA)  : India’s biggest producer of the
alloy said first-quarter sales rose to 1.59 million metric tons
from 1.4 million tons a year earlier, according to an e-mailed
statement. The shares rose 0.1 to 597.85 rupees.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Andrew Macaskill in  New Delhi  at 
 amacaskill@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
